  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are Some interesting facts of Langar at golden temple?",
  "response": "The Langar at the Golden Temple in Amritsar, also known as the Guru Ka Langar, is a fascinating aspect of Sikh culture and tradition. Here are some interesting facts about it:\n\n1. **World's Largest Community Kitchen**: The Golden Temple's Langar is recognized as the world's largest community kitchen, serving free meals to around 100,000 people every day. During peak times, this number can exceed 150,000.\n\n2. **Volunteer-Driven**: The Langar is entirely run by volunteers, known as \"sewadars.\" People from all walks of life, regardless of religion, caste, or nationality, can participate in preparing, cooking, and serving the meals. This spirit of selfless service is a core principle of Sikhism.\n\n3. **24/7 Operation**: The Langar operates 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. At any time of day or night, visitors can partake in a free meal, showcasing the Sikh commitment to hospitality and service.\n\n4. **Simple Yet Nutritious Meals**: The meals served are simple but nutritious, typically consisting of lentil soup (daal), vegetables, and flatbread (roti or chapati). Sometimes, rice and sweets are also included. Everything is vegetarian to accommodate all visitors.\n\n5. **Egalitarian Seating**: In the Langar hall, everyone sits on the floor and eats together, symbolizing equality and the breaking down of social barriers. This practice embodies the Sikh belief in the equality of all human beings.\n\n6. **Massive Scale of Operations**: The kitchen uses around 5,000 kg of wheat flour, 1,800 kg of lentils, 1,400 kg of rice, 5,000 liters of milk, 1,000 kg of sugar, and 5,000 kg of vegetables daily. Volunteers work tirelessly to prepare these vast quantities of food.\n\n7. **Environmental Sustainability**: The Golden Temple has implemented eco-friendly practices in its Langar operations. For instance, it uses solar power to help run the kitchen, and it has a system for managing waste and recycling materials.\n\n8. **Historical Significance**: The tradition of Langar was started by Guru Nanak Dev Ji, the founder of Sikhism, and formalized by Guru Amar Das Ji, the third Sikh Guru. It was designed to promote the idea of equality and community service.\n\n9. **Open to All**: The Langar is open to people of all faiths and backgrounds. It is a powerful symbol of inclusivity and the Sikh ethos of universal love and service.\n\n10. **Educational and Inspirational**: Many visitors and volunteers come away from their experience at the Langar with a deep appreciation for the principles of Sikhism. It serves as an educational tool, spreading the message of unity and selfless service around the world.\n\nThese facts highlight the incredible organization and spiritual significance of the Langar at the Golden Temple, making it not just a place for nourishment but a beacon of Sikh values and community spirit.",
